===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|countable}} A quantity of something that is part of the whole amount or number.
#* {{RQ:Chmbrs YngrSt|VI}}
#*: “I don't mean all of your friends—only a small '''proportion'''—which, however, connects your circle with that deadly, idle, brainless bunch—the insolent chatterers at the opera, the gorged dowagers, the worn-out, passionless men, the enervated matrons of the summer capital,{{nb...}}!”
# {{lb|en|uncountable}} Harmonious relation of parts to each other or to the whole.
# {{lb|en|countable}} Proper or equal share.
#* {{w|Jeremy Taylor}} (1613–1677)
#*: Let the women{{...}}do the same things in their '''proportions''' and capacities.
# The relation of one part to another or to the whole with respect to magnitude, quantity, or degree.
#: {{ux|en|the '''proportion''' of the parts of a building, or of the body}}
#* {{w|Lancelot Ridley}} (ca.1500-1576)
#*: The image of Christ, made after his own '''proportion'''.
#* Sir {{w|Walter Scott}} (1771-1832)
#*: Formed in the best '''proportions''' of her sex.
#* {{w|Thomas Babington Macaulay, 1st Baron Macaulay|Thomas Macaulay}} (1800-1859)
#*: Documents are authentic and facts are true precisely in '''proportion''' to the support which they afford to his theory.
# {{lb|en|mathematics|countable}} A [[statement]] of [[equality]] between two [[ratio]]s.
# {{lb|en|countable|chiefly|in the plural}} [[size|Size]].
#* {{quote-book|year=1898|author={{w|Winston Churchill (novelist)|Winston Churchill}}
|title={{w|The Celebrity}}|chapter=8
|passage=The humor of my proposition appealed more strongly to Miss Trevor than I had looked for, and from that time forward she became her old self again;{{...}}. Now she had come to look upon the matter in its true '''proportions''', and her anticipation of a possible chance of teaching him a lesson was a pleasure to behold.}}
#* {{quote-news|date=May 20, 2012|author=Nathan Rabin
|title=[http://www.avclub.com/articles/marge-gets-a-job,73723/ TV: Review: THE SIMPSONS (CLASSIC): “Marge Gets A Job” (season 4, episode 7; originally aired 11/05/1992)]
|work=The Onion AV Club
|passage=What other television show would feature a gorgeously designed sequence where a horrifically mutated Pierre and Marie Curie, their bodies swollen to Godzilla-like '''proportions''' from prolonged exposure to the radiation that would eventually kill them, destroy an Asian city with their bare hands like vengeance-crazed monster-Gods?}}

